What a week for US banking!! I thought I would do a #datavisualisation on it.

I've used a force simulation of the 144 regional banks that make up the S&P Regional Banks Select Industry Index.

So what sparked all this? It was of course the collapse of First Republic Bank, which sent shockwaves through the US banking system. Questions now being raised about the strength of the US banking system and the wider economy.

It's the US' second-largest bank failure, after the Silicon Valley Bank collapse. It's crazy to think that three of the four largest bank failures in US history have taken place in the last two months.

The Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) took control of First Republic Bank on Monday and brokered a deal with JPMorgan Chase, which will protect deposits but wipe out shareholders and make the largest U.S. bank even bigger.

While it is unclear whether First Republic Bank is the final domino to fall in the recent banking crisis, the sector as a whole is flush with paper losses on investments. That's the reason for this data visualisation.
